The municipality of Zubří lies in the region of the Highlands, about 3.5 km northeast of the New Town on
Moravia, which is an extended commune. The areas of interest are located in the municipality's intravilan.
Zubří is located in the area of the New Town Hills, which is part of the Bítešská Highlands.
The characteristic flat surface of the upland is due to the resilience of the rock. Highest
The point is the top of Harus Hill (741 m above sea level). The landscape consists of fields, meadows and spruce stands

5. A brief history of Zubří Municipality
The local name tooth is interpreted as "the place where the dentists are." Proper interpretation
is justified by interpretations of similar local names, such as Deer, Trout, etc. (Hosák -
The oldest written record attesting to the existence of the municipality dates back to 1348, when Jimram
from Stone with his sons transfers the Zubří village to the ownership of the Ješka brothers among other goods
and Benes of Boskovic (Capture et al. 1856, 1). In 1358, Jesek acquires part of Bystřice and others
belonging to the Moravian Margrave Jan Jindřich of Luxembourg. The tooth is not by name
mentioned, but it can be assumed that it was also among these estates, as it was two years earlier
later (1360) the Moravian Margrave John transfers his share of the Bystřice along with other villages
Janu z Boskovic and at this event Zubří is mentioned (Hosák 2004, 71). In the years to come
The tooth once again went into Luxembourg's possession. In 1384, margarita Yošt Moravský gives
(Luxembourg) in fiefdom castle Pyšolec with works by Bystřice and several villages (among them Zubří)
Heralto of Kunsttate. Heralt gives these goods sometime before 1417 as collateral to Blud of the Rabbits. After
Heralto's death is paid back by Boček Kuna of Kunsttate and Podebrad (ibid, 335). Then
Pernštejno's masters (ibid, 71) take over the pyšolec and stream estates. In 1585 they sell
John and Maxmilan of Pernstein's New Town Domain, which at the time included Zubø, William
Dubski of Trebomislic. Since then, the fate of the tooth has been closely linked to the New City. Mon. 1620
the estate of the lords of Třebomyslice was confiscated and subsequently sold to Prince Francis in 1624
Cardinal of Ditrichštejn. His heir Maximilian of Ditrichštejn sells it to 1638 Shimon
The Kratzers of Schensberk. His son, Francis Maximilian, runs the estates after Shimon's death.
But he mismanaged the acquired property so badly that he mortgaged the estate, and then
was also withdrawn by the court's ruling. Thus, 1691 falls back into the hands of the Ditrichštejn. Ti
then the estates advance to the so-called Marian School in Brno (Foundation Institute of Nobles) (ibid, 74).
According to the municipal law of 1849, the municipality has become the lowest unit of political administration since 1850.
On the basis of this law, a new political and judicial organization of the Crown
the county general and the judicial district of the New Town (Fuks
2010, 1). As part of the large-scale merging of municipalities in the 2nd century, Zubor was connected in 1980
to the New Town in Moravia. It has regained its autonomy following a change in political circumstances

A fraction of a duck was found in Probe 4 (SJ 125) whose front heating wall is decorated with
geometric ornament complete with a plant motif (Annex: Figure 19; Table 1). This

found in the village of Jimramov (district of Žďár nad Sázavou) in archaeological research
